---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, "");
---

<Base
  title="The name — Otlyra"
  description="Why the browser is called Otlyra, how to say it, and the legend nobody asked for."
>
  <h1>Otlyra</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Ot·ly·ra</strong>, said <em>OT-lee-ra</em>. Three syllables, stress on
    the first.
  </p>

  <p>
    The <strong>Ot</strong> is from <a href="https://github.com/octofhir/otter">Otter</a>,
    which is what the browser is built on and what the mark is a picture of. The
    rest is <em>lyra</em> — a lyre, and the constellation named after one.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this one</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>It keeps the <code>Ot</code> that ties the browser to Otter.</li>
    <li>It does not read like a crate name. A browser is a thing people open, not a dependency they add.</li>
    <li>It is short enough to be a binary: <code>otlyra</code>.</li>
    <li>It works for the browser, for the interface engine, and for the organisation, without any of the three sounding borrowed.</li>
    <li>Searching for it turned up no existing product, company, browser or repository. Whether the domain is free is a question for a registrar rather than for a search engine.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The legend</h2>
  <blockquote>
    <p>
      An otter carries one favourite stone its whole life, tucked in the pocket
      of loose skin under its arm. It is not sentiment. It is a tool: everything
      the river closes — a clam, a mussel, a snail — the otter opens by knowing
      exactly where the shell is weak and striking there, and nowhere else.
    </p>
    <p>
      The story goes that one otter, floating on its back in the usual way, found
      a lyre drifting down the river with its strings still on. It set the lyre on
      its chest where the stone normally went, and struck a shell against it out of
      habit. The shell opened. So did the note.
    </p>
    <p>
      From then on the otter could hear the structure of a thing before it broke
      it: which part was holding the rest together, and which part was only in the
      way. It stopped hammering. It started listening, and then it opened things
      on the first try.
    </p>
  </blockquote>
  <p>
    Which is a long way of saying: a browser is a machine for turning bytes into
    a structure, and the useful ones let you <em>see</em> the structure rather
    than guess at it from the pixels. That is what the
    <a href={`${base}/devtools/`}>inspector</a> is for, and it is why the same
    answers are on the wire for <a href={`${base}/agents/`}>a program</a> to ask
    for.
  </p>
  <p style="color: var(--dim)">
    No otters were involved in the naming. The lyre is, as far as anyone can
    establish, entirely made up.
  </p>

  <h2>The mark</h2>
  <p>
    An otter, face on, half out of the water. The ring behind it runs violet to
    cyan through blue, and every accent on this site is a point on that same run —
    so the palette has one source rather than a designer's opinion of one.
  </p>
  <div class="marks">
    <img src={`${base}/logo-circle.png`} alt="Otlyra's otter in a circle" width="84" height="84" />
    <img src={`${base}/logo-square.png`} alt="Otlyra's otter in a rounded square" width="84" height="84" />
    <img src={`${base}/logo-chrome.png`} alt="Otlyra's otter as a browser chrome mark" width="84" height="84" />
    <img src={`${base}/logo-line.png`} alt="Otlyra's otter as a line drawing" width="84" height="84" />
  </div>
  <p>
    The circle is the one on this page and in the tab bar of your browser. The
    rounded square is the application icon, which is the shape macOS wants. The
    line drawing is for places that get one colour and no say in which — a stamp
    on a diagram, a terminal, a print.
  </p>
</Base>
